<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-556-009  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 556 009.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 29 1990 v24 n43 p27(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Justice neither delayed nor denied. (information systems inFlorida courts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Florida's Eighth Judicial Circuit Court in uses the CriminalJustice Information System (CJIS) to keep track of criminalrecords.andP;  The information system is an offender-based trackingsystem that is composed of a network of computers and performs thewhole scheduling and docketing process for every misdemeanor andfelony in the circuit.andP;  CJIS, which was installed in early 1990,also generates arrest, sentencing, bail and case managementreports much faster and less expensively than was previouslythought possible.andP;  Florida officials estimate the informationsystem will save the state counties around $500,000 a year ascrime increases, caseloads multiply and jail populations grow.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FloridaInformation SystemsLegal ApplicationsTrendsCase Study.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>